According to the {{ill|Dhammapada|ja|ダンマパダ|12=draft}} (Verses of the Law), in a past life, Kalpina prayed before the Buddha Padumuttara and aspired to his position as Foremost in Knowledge of the Constellations. As a guild leader of weavers, he offered alms to 1,000 {{ill|Paccekabuddha|ja|縁覚|12=draft}} monks, thus earning merit that led to his rebirth in the heavens. Later, he offered further support to the Buddhist monastic community during the age of {{ill|Kassapa Buddha|ja|迦葉仏|12=draft}}, which paved the way for his present life as the king of Kukutabhani City. His queen, named Anoja (from the people of {{lang|sa|Saagala}}), also followed the path of Buddhism and eventually ordained as a nun.

== Career ==
After Shakyamuni visited his hometown of {{ill|Kapilavastu|ja|カピラ城|12=draft}} and resumed his wandering teachings, Kalpina joined the monastic order along with prominent disciples such as {{ill|Anuruddha|ja|阿那律|12=draft}}, {{ill|Upāli|ja|優波離|12=draft}}, and Nandika (難提迦). Shakyamuni guided him with teachings, leading Kalpina to achieve enlightenment. Renowned for his deep meditative practices and solitary focus, he was described as having lived a privileged life where food was so abundant it was believed to "arise from the storehouse."

