Kalpina is said to be from the {{ill|Kosala Kingdom|ja|十六大国#コーサラ王国|12=draft|12=draft}}. One tradition holds that his parents prayed to the {{ill|Scorpius|ja|さそり座|12=draft|12=draft}} constellation (known in Japan as "Soiboshi" or the 16th star of Scorpius) for his birth, which influenced his name. Several accounts exist regarding his background:

# He was the son of a {{ill|Kshatriya|ja|クシャトリア|12=draft|12=draft}} (royal family) in a border region called Kukuta and ascended to the throne after his father. He sought knowledge by sending envoys to all four directions. Learning from merchants about Shakyamuni Buddha residing in the {{ill|Jetavana Monastery|ja|祇園精舎|1=Jetavana|lt=Jetavana monastery|12=draft|12=draft}}, he traveled east to seek teachings. Along the way, he encountered heavy rain by the Chandanbhaga River and stayed in a potter's hut. Shakyamuni, aware of his arrival, disguised himself as an elderly monk and joined him, eventually leading Kalpina to become his disciple. ({{ill|Theragatha|ja|長老の偈|12=draft|12=draft}}, verses 547–556)
# He was the king of Suvarnabhumi (Gold Land), identified as a coastal region of {{ill|Myanmar|ja|ビルマ|12=draft|12=draft}}, ruling over 36,000 subordinate states. When he sent a message to {{ill|King Pasenadi|ja|波斯匿王|12=draft|12=draft}} of Kosala demanding surrender, Shakyamuni, in the guise of a {{ill|Chakravarti (ideal king)|ja|転輪聖王|12=draft|12=draft}}, revealed the limits of his power. Kalpina realized his own shortcomings and became a devoted disciple, renouncing his throne to join the Buddhist monastic community. (References: {{ill|The Sutra of Wise and Foolish|ja|賢愚経|12=draft|12=draft}}, Volume 7, Chapter 36, and {{ill|The Hundred Stories Sutra|ja|撰集百縁経|12=draft|12=draft}}, Volume 9, Chapter 88)

