# He was the son of a {{ill|Kshatriya|ja|クシャトリア|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kshatriya|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to クシャトリヤ}} (royal family) in a border region called Kukuta and ascended to the throne after his father. He sought knowledge by sending envoys to all four directions. Learning from merchants about Shakyamuni Buddha residing in the [[:en:Jetavana|Jetavana monastery]], he traveled east to seek teachings. Along the way, he encountered heavy rain by the Chandanbhaga River and stayed in a potter's hut. Shakyamuni, aware of his arrival, disguised himself as an elderly monk and joined him, eventually leading Kalpina to become his disciple. ({{ill|Theragatha|ja|長老の偈|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Theragatha|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, verses 547–556) # He was the king of Suvarnabhumi (Gold Land), identified as a coastal region of {{ill|Myanmar|ja|ビルマ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Myanmar|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to ミャンマー}}, ruling over 36,000 subordinate states. When he sent a message to {{ill|King Pasenadi|ja|波斯匿王|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/King Pasenadi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to プラセーナジット}} of Kosala demanding surrender, Shakyamuni, in the guise of a [[:en:Chakravarti (Sanskrit term)|Chakravarti (ideal king)]], revealed the limits of his power. Kalpina realized his own shortcomings and became a devoted disciple, renouncing his throne to join the Buddhist monastic community. (References: [[:en:Sutra of the Wise and the Fool|The Sutra of Wise and Foolish]], Volume 7, Chapter 36, and {{ill|The Hundred Stories Sutra|ja|撰集百縁経|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/The Hundred Stories Sutra|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, Volume 9, Chapter 88)
== Past Life == According to the {{ill|Dhammapada|ja|ダンマパダ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dhammapada|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 法句経}} (Verses of the Law), in a past life, Kalpina prayed before the Buddha Padumuttara and aspired to his position as Foremost in Knowledge of the Constellations. As a guild leader of weavers, he offered alms to 1,000 {{ill|Paccekabuddha|ja|縁覚|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Paccekabuddha|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} monks, thus earning merit that led to his rebirth in the heavens. Later, he offered further support to the Buddhist monastic community during the age of {{ill|Kassapa Buddha|ja|迦葉仏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kassapa Buddha|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, which paved the way for his present life as the king of Kukutabhani City. His queen, named Anoja (from the people of {{lang|sa|Saagala}}), also followed the path of Buddhism and eventually ordained as a nun.
== Career == After Shakyamuni visited his hometown of [[:en:Kapilavastu (ancient city)|Kapilavastu]] and resumed his wandering teachings, Kalpina joined the monastic order along with prominent disciples such as [[:en:Aniruddha (Buddhist)|Anuruddha]], [[:en:Upāli|Upāli]], and Nandika (難提迦). Shakyamuni guided him with teachings, leading Kalpina to achieve enlightenment. Renowned for his deep meditative practices and solitary focus, he was described as having lived a privileged life where food was so abundant it was believed to "arise from the storehouse."
